      guide: `${a} and ${b} create a useful conflict. One force may want speed where the other wants depth, release where the other wants structure, desire where the other wants restraint, or order where the other wants wildness. In human terms, this is the place where a real choice has to be made. The friction is not failure; it is energy asking for a more honest form.`,
      narration: `${a} and ${b} do not immediately agree. Their meeting produces heat. The pressure point is ${friction}. Do not rush to reconcile it. The tension is the teaching. It shows where two values, instincts, or loyalties are competing for authority. Yet ${bridge} remains in the field, which means the conflict is not meaningless. It has a way through, but not by denial. Hold both forces clearly. Let the edge stay visible. The chamber asks what strength could be made if the tension were faced directly instead of softened into politeness.`
